# File naming (`protocol/`)

Pattern: **`{domain}.{purpose}.{extension}`**

- **domain** — scope (e.g. `chat`, `intent`, `profile`, `opportunity`)
- **purpose** — role/type (see table)

## Common purposes

| purpose | role | example |
|---------|------|---------|
| `graph` | LangGraph workflow | `chat.graph.ts` |
| `state` | graph/app state | `chat.state.ts` |
| `agent` | LLM agent | `chat.agent.ts` |
| `generator` | generates text/artifacts | `hyde.generator.ts` |
| `evaluator` | scoring | `opportunity.evaluator.ts` |
| `verifier` | validation | `intent.verifier.ts` |
| `inferrer` | inference | `intent.inferrer.ts` |
| `reconciler` | merge/reconcile | `intent.reconciler.ts` |
| `controller` | HTTP layer | `chat.controller.ts` |
| `service` | business logic | `intent.service.ts` |
| `queue` | BullMQ / jobs | `intent.queue.ts` |
| `spec` | tests (often `*.spec.ts`) | `router.agent.spec.ts` |

**Adapters** (under `src/adapters/`): **`{concept}.adapter.ts`** by capability, not tech — see adapters rule.

## Exceptions

`index.ts`, `schema.ts`, `main.ts`, and small root-level utilities (`constants.ts`, `types.ts`) are exempt.

## Good vs bad

- Good: `chat.graph.ts`, `opportunity.evaluator.ts`, `intent.reconciler.ts`
- Bad: `chatGraph.ts`, `intentAgent.ts`, bare `generator.ts`

## New file

1. Pick **domain** (area). 2. Pick **purpose** (type). 3. Name: **`{domain}.{purpose}.ts`** (e.g. message validation → `message.validator.ts`).
